dataIdInfo.idPurp: The CEC Natural Gas Pipeline geospatial data layer contains interstate and intrastate gas pipelines throughout California. These pipelines represent the midstream transportation routes of natural gas after it has left the gathering systems until it reaches the local distribution systems. Clipped to Delta.
dataIdInfo.idAbs:
The natural gas station and pipeline mapping database was started in 2011 and completed in 2012. The enterprise GIS system on CEC's critical infrastructure database was leaded by GIS Services Unit in November 2014 and was implemented in May 2016.

The data was derived and rectified from PennWell natural gas pipeline geospatial data. Historical maps provided by CEC/Energy Assessments Division were used as references. The sources for the natural gas pipeline digitizing are including sub-meter resolution of Digital Globe, Bing, Google, ESRI and NAIP aerial imageries, with scale at least 1:10,000. Occasionally, USGS Topographic map, Google Street View and Bing Bird's Eye are used to verify the precise location and station type of a facility. Since most of the natural gas pipelines are underground, it is almost impossible to digitize the lines with aerial imagery. A thin trail alike adjacent to or overlap with the PennWell pipeline data was digitized with the aerial imagery. In the near future, additional attributes and distribution pipeline data will be added based on NPMS data.
